{{more footnotes|date=March 2011}} {{italics title}} '''''Jus exclusivae''''' ([[Latin]] for "right of exclusion"; sometimes called the '''papal veto''') was the right claimed by several [[Catholic]] [[monarch]]s of [[Europe]] to veto a candidate for the [[Pope|papacy]]. The [[French monarchy|French monarch]], the [[Spanish monarchy|Spanish monarch]], the [[Holy Roman Emperor]], and the [[Emperor of Austria]] claimed this right at various times, making known to a [[papal conclave]], through a [[crown-cardinal]], that the monarch deemed a particular candidate for the papacy objectionable.
==Early history== The right exercised by [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] emperors and Holy Roman Emperors to confirm the election of a Pope, which was last exercised in the [[Early Middle Ages]], appears unrelated to the legal claim of ''jus exclusivae'', during the 17th century, when [[treatise]]s in defence of this right first appear. Spain, which ruled much of Italy at the time, raised the claim in 1605 and again in 1644 at the conclave that elected Cardinal [[Pope Innocent X|Giovanni Battista Pamphili]] (who became [[Pope Innocent X]]) to exclude Cardinal Sacchetti.
== Right asserted since 1644 == [[File:Emperor_Francis_Joseph.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Franz Joseph I of Austria]] was the last monarch to attempt to exercise the ''jus exclusivae''.]] *[[Papal conclave, 1644]] – [[Giulio Cesare Sacchetti]], by [[Philip IV of Spain]]<ref name=mp>{{cite book|page=52 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=KjsqDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA52& | title = Electing the Pope in Early Modern Italy, 1450-1700 | first= Miles | last= Pattenden | publisher =Oxford University Press | date= 2017}}</ref> *[[Papal conclave, 1655]] – [[Giulio Cesare Sacchetti]], by [[Philip IV of Spain]]<ref name=mp/> *[[Papal conclave, 1669–70]] – [[Innocent XI|Benedetto Odescalchi]], by [[Louis XIV]] of France<ref name=mp/>{{efn|Cardinal Odeschalchi was elected pope in 1676, taking the name Innocent XI.}} *[[Papal conclave, 1700]] – [[Galeazzo Marescotti]], by [[Louis XIV]] of France<ref name=mp/> *[[Papal conclave, 1721]] – [[Fabrizio Paolucci]], by the Emperor [[Charles VI, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles VI]]; and [[Francesco Pignatelli]] by [[Philip V of Spain]] *[[Papal conclave, 1730]] – [[Giuseppe Renato Imperiali]], by [[Philip V of Spain]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Petruccelli della Gattina| first1=Ferdinando |title=Histoire diplomatique des conclaves| date=1866| publisher=A. Lacrois, Verboeckhoven & Co.|location =Brussels| page=68|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c08VAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA68&| accessdate=28 November 2017 |language=fr}}</ref> *[[Papal conclave, 1758]] – [[Carlo Alberto Guidoboni Cavalchini]], by [[Louis XV of France]]<ref>{{cite book| page = 403 | title = Keepers of the Keys of Heaven: A History of the Papacy | date= 2009 |url =https://books.google.com/books?id=C3qvU0-tatkC&pg=PT375& | publisher = Basic Books | first = Roger | last = Collins }}</ref> *[[Papal conclave, 1774–75]] - [[Giovanni Carlo Boschi]], by the [[House of Bourbon|Bourbon]] courts<ref name=mp/> *[[Papal conclave, 1823]] – {{ill|Antonio Gabriele Severoli|it}} by [[Francis I of Austria]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Burkle-Young|first1=Francis A.|title=Papal Elections in the Age of Transition, 1878-1922|date=2000|publisher=Lexington Books|page=22|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t9QxJMdp6FMC&pg=PA22&|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=pennington>{{cite book|last1=Pennington|first1=Arthur Robert|title=The Papal Conclaves|date=1897|publisher=E. & J.B. Young & Co.|location=New York|page=37|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AlFDAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA37&|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref> *[[Papal conclave, 1830–31]] – [[Giacomo Giustiniani]], by [[Ferdinand VII of Spain]]<ref>{{cite book| accessdate = 25 November 2017 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=BBM3AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA617& | page=617 | title = The Chair of Peter: Or the Papacy Considered in its Institution, Development and Organization | first= John Nicholas | last=Murphy | location = London | publisher = Burns & Oates | date= 1886}}</ref><ref name=pennington/> *[[Papal conclave, 1903]] – [[Mariano Rampolla]], by [[Franz Joseph I of Austria|Franz Joseph I]] of [[Austria-Hungary]]<ref>{{cite book| first1=Josef |last1=Schmidlin |first2= Anton |last2=de Waal|title=Life of His Holiness Pope Pius X|date=1904| publisher= Benziger Brothers| pages=186ff.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AmQJAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA186&|accessdate=17 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Career of Pius and his Policy |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1914/08/20/101431923.pdf |accessdate=23 July 2018 |work=New York Times |date=20 August 1914}}</ref>
At the 1846 conclave, Austrian Chancellor [[Klemens von Metternich]] confided Austria's veto of [[Pius IX|Cardinal Giovanni Maria Mastai-Ferretti]] to [[Cardinal Carlo Gaetano Gaisruck]], [[Archbishop of Milan]], who arrived too late.<ref>{{cite book | first= M. | last= Ott | url = http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/12134b.htm | accessdate = 16 November 2017 | date= 1911 | publisher = Robert Appleton Company | title= Catholic Encyclopedia| chapter= Pope Pius IX}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| page=328 | first=Valérie | last=Pirie | chapter-url = http://www.pickle-publishing.com/papers/triple-crown-pius-ix.htm | title= The Triple Crown: An Account of the Papal Conclaves | location = London | date=1935 | publisher = Sidgwick & Jackson | chapter = Pius IX (Mastai-Ferretti) | accessdate = 16 November 2017}}</ref>{{efn|Salvador Miranda writes that Eugenio Cazzani calls the report that Gaisruck was bringing the Austrian Emperor's veto of Mastai-Ferretti an unverified rumor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.fiu.edu/~mirandas/bios1824-ii.htm#Gaysruck |title=Gaisruck, Karl Kajetan von |author=Salvador Miranda|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = Cazzani | first = Eugenio | title = Vescovi e arcivescovi di Milano | publisher = Massimo | location = Milano | year = 1996 | isbn = 88-7030-891-X |pages=266–269 |language=Italian}}</ref>}}
== Papal attitude toward the ''jus exclusivae'' == The right has never been formally recognized by the papacy, though conclaves have considered it expedient to recognize secular objections to certain ''[[papabile|papabili]]'', that is, candidates for the papacy, and to accept secular interference as an unavoidable abuse. By the [[papal bull]] ''In eligendis'' of 9 October 1562 [[Pope Pius IV]] ordered the cardinals to elect a pope without deference to any secular power. The bull ''Aeterni Patris Filius'' (of 15 November 1621) forbids cardinals to conspire to exclude any candidate. These pronouncements however, did not specifically condemn the ''jus exclusivae''. In the apostolic constitution ''In hac sublimi'' of 23 August 1871 [[Pope Pius IX]] forbad any kind of secular interference in papal elections.
The most recent attempt to exercise the right to exclude [[Cardinal Rampolla]] in 1903 was rejected by the conclave, although over the course of several ballots Rampolla, who had been the leading candidate, lost support until the conclave elected Cardinal Sarto, [[Pius X]]. The following year, Pius X forbad the ''jus exclusivae'' in the apostolic constitution ''Commissum Nobis'' of 20 January 1904:
{{Quote|Wherefore in virtue of holy obedience, under threat of the Divine judgment, and pain of excommunication [[latae sententiae]]… we prohibit the cardinals of the Holy Roman Church, all and single, and likewise the Secretary of the Sacred College of Cardinals, and all others who take part in the conclave, to receive even under the form of a simple desire the office of proposing the veto in whatever manner, either by writing or by word of mouth… And it is our will that this prohibition be extended… to all intercessions, etc… by which the lay powers endeavour to intrude themselves in the election of a pontiff… Let no man infringe this our inhibition… under pain of incurring the indignation of God Almighty and of his Apostles, Sts. Peter and Paul.}}
Since then the cardinals in conclave have been enjoined to take this oath: "We shall never in any way accept, under any pretext, from any civil power whatever, the office of proposing a veto of exclusion even under the form of a mere desire… and we shall never lend favour to any intervention, or intercession, or any other method whatever, by which the lay powers of any grade or order may wish to interfere in the election of a pontiff."
No power has openly attempted to exercise the right since 1903. France had become a republic in 1870. After World War I, there was no German Empire and no Austrian Empire. Spain became a republic and eventually became a constitutional monarchy. During the [[Papal conclave, 1963|1963 conclave]], Generalissimo [[Francisco Franco]] made an unsuccessful attempt to block the election of Cardinal [[Pope Paul VI|Giovanni Montini]]. He sent the [[College of Cardinals]] some "advice" through Cardinal [[Arcadio Larraona Saralegui|Arcadio Larraona]], a native of Spain who was then the Prefect of the [[Sacred Congregation of Rites|Congregation of Rites]]. It was carefully drafted to fall outside the forms of influence that Pius X had prohibited, but the cardinals nevertheless thought it outrageous.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Burkle-Young|first1=Francis A.|title=Papal Elections in the Age of Transition, 1878-1922|date=2000|publisher=Lexington Books| page=160|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t9QxJMdp6FMC&pg=PA160&|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref>{{efn|Just after the conclave ended, the ''[[New York Times]]'' reported: "A report before the beginning of the conclave that Generalissimo Francisco Franco had asked the six Spanish cardinals to prevent Cardinal Montini's elevation was emphatically denied. The Spanish press had criticized [Montini] last October after he had publicly interceded with [Franco] for political prisoners."<ref>{{cite news | work = New York Times | date = 22 June 1963 | accessdate = 17 November 2017 | url = https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1963/06/22/82068997.pdf | title = Rome Believes New Pope Will Press for Reforms | first=Paul | last = Hofmann }}</ref>}}
